<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06289145 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06289145 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  What's a tenor to do? Plenty of adults would gladly have given up watching theAnita Hill-Clarence Thomas hearings Sunday to attend a concert by LucianoPavarotti in Detroit. Instead, the renowned opera star, seen here in a pastperformance of &quot;Rigoletto,&quot; was up against a tough crowd at a performanceattended by public school students. &quot;I like rap better, this music is tooadvanced for me,&quot; observed Daveatta Williams, a freshman at Northern HighSchool. She said she almost fell asleep. Williams was among about 1,000 whoattended the concert at Joe Louis Arena. Ford Motor Co. purchased the$100-a-seat tickets for the students.;   &quot;He screamed too loud,&quot; said AaronTaylor, a sixth-grader at Thirkell Middle School.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  A RAP ON OPERA  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  People.  </MEMO><TEXT>     But Aaron's older brother, Harry, was instantly charmed by Pavarotti.&quot;Wow,&quot; said Harry, 15, a Northern High sophomore. &quot;I'll never forget this,&quot; hesaid. &quot;Someone once told me that anything that encourages beauty is art. Thisis art.&quot;;   From the mouths of 15-year-olds . . .  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Compiled from Mercury News wire services.  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911015  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  October  </MONTH><PG.COL>  4A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  171  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday, October 15, 199100289145,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>